The paper deals with the problem of untangling a planar graph, which involves manipulating the vertices of the graph to obtain a planar drawing. This problem is closely related to computational geometry (cs.CG) and graph theory (cs.DS). The paper also discusses the complexity of computing and approximating the minimum number of vertex movements required to untangle a given drawing, which falls under the category of computational complexity (cs.CC). Additionally, the paper presents an algorithm for fixing a certain number of vertices when untangling a drawing, which involves combinatorial and probabilistic techniques that are relevant to discrete mathematics (cs.DM) and graph theory (cs.GT).
